# Mission Overview
The primary goal of Landsat 9 is Data Continuity. By orbiting in the same path as Landsat 8 but 8 days out of phase, the two satellites provide an 8-day revisit time for any spot on Earth.

.panelset[
.panel[.panel-name[Mission Goals]

Reliability: Provide a "gold standard" for calibrated land imaging.

Sustainability: Monitor global land use and change.

Open Data: Ensure free and open access to high-quality science data through the USGS archive.
]

.panel[.panel-name[Scientific Evidence]

Temporal Consistency: 50-year record allows for longitudinal climate studies.

Radiometric Resolution: 14-bit OLI-2 sensor provides higher signal-to-noise ratio than previous missions.

Global Coverage: Captures up to 750 scenes per day, expanding the global archive.
]
]

---
# Why 8 Days?

.pull-left[
* Landsat 8 and 9 are in the same orbit.
* They are offset by **180 degrees**.
* This "constellation" doubling effectively halves the temporal resolution from 16 days to 8 days.
]

.pull-right[
### The Impact
Better tracking of:
* Crop growth cycles.
* Rapid deforestation.
* Glacial retreat.
* Natural disaster recovery.
]

